<paragraph id="7C54242D2E77EF69FCCEF888FCFE7F4A" blockId="10.[189,1399,1586,2010]" lastBlockId="11.[189,1399,267,1098]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">
<subSubSection id="34F177A62E77EF68FCCEF888FAC3795E" box="[872,1398,1884,1914]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="vernacular_names">
– Galapagos shark; Tubarão-dos-Galápos 
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E77EF68FA93F8B4FAFA795E" bold="true" box="[1333,1359,1884,1911]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">②</emphasis>
, 
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E77EF68FAFAF8B4FAC3795E" bold="true" box="[1372,1398,1884,1911]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">③</emphasis>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="34F177A62E77EF69FF54F869FCFE7F4A" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="12" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" type="discussion">
According to 
<bibRefCitation id="187A59DC2E77EF68FE2FF869FD1279B0" author="Ebert D. A. &amp; Stehmann M. F. W." box="[393,679,1921,1945]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" refId="ref39845" refString="Ebert D. A. &amp; Stehmann M. F. W. 2013. Sharks, batoids, and chimaeras of the North Atlantic. FAO Species Catalogue for Fishery Purposes no. 7, Food and Agriculture Organization, Rome." type="journal volume" year="2013">
Ebert &amp; Stehmann (
<date id="085502ED2E77EF68FDC3F869FD2A79B0" box="[613,671,1921,1945]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" value="2013">2013</date>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, the species 
<taxonomicName id="BBEB5FAE2E77EF68FC92F869FB8579B0" baseAuthorityName="Lesueur" baseAuthorityYear="1818" box="[820,1072,1921,1945]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Carcharhinidae" genus="Carcharhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obscurus">
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E77EF68FC92F869FB8579B0" box="[820,1072,1921,1945]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">Carcharhinus obscurus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is very closely related to this species (
<taxonomicName id="BBEB5FAE2E77EF68FEF4F84AFDB47990" baseAuthorityName="Snodgrass &amp; Heller" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[338,513,1953,1977]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Carcharhinidae" genus="Carcharhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E77EF68FEF4F84AFED17990" box="[338,356,1954,1977]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E77EF68FED2F849FDB47990" box="[372,513,1953,1977]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="11">galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and they are difficult to distinguish from each other. Recent molecular studies suggest that these two species may in fact be a single one, with one of the two forms being found 
<taxonomicName id="BBEB5FAE2E77EF68FABBF829FA8E79F0" box="[1309,1339,1985,2009]" pageId="10" pageNumber="11" rank="species" species="far">far</taxonomicName>
from landmasses (
<taxonomicName id="BBEB5FAE2E76EF69FED9FEE4FD857F0A" baseAuthorityName="Snodgrass &amp; Heller" baseAuthorityYear="1905" box="[383,560,267,291]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Carcharhinidae" genus="Carcharhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="galapagensis">
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E76EF69FED9FEE4FE247F0A" box="[383,401,268,291]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E76EF69FE05FEE3FD857F0A" box="[419,560,267,291]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">galapagensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) and the other one (
<taxonomicName id="BBEB5FAE2E76EF69FCBAFEE4FC2A7F0A" baseAuthorityName="Lesueur" baseAuthorityYear="1818" box="[796,927,267,291]" class="Elasmobranchii" family="Carcharhinidae" genus="Carcharhinus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Carcharhiniformes" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obscurus">
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E76EF69FCBAFEE4FC2A7F0A" box="[796,927,267,291]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<collectionCodeEnum id="6080600F2E76EF69FCBAFEE4FC847F0A" box="[796,817,268,291]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">C</collectionCodeEnum>
. obscurus
</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) occurring in association with continental shelves and upper slopes (
<collectionCodeEnum id="6080600F2E76EF69FDACFEC3FD947F6A" box="[522,545,299,323]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">G</collectionCodeEnum>
. Naylor, pers comm. 
<emphasis id="4E9FF83F2E76EF69FCA0FEC4FCAE7F6A" box="[774,795,300,323]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">in</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="187A59DC2E76EF69FC84FEC3FB9C7F6A" author="Ebert D. A. &amp; Stehmann M. F. W." box="[802,1065,299,323]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref39845" refString="Ebert D. A. &amp; Stehmann M. F. W. 2013. Sharks, batoids, and chimaeras of the North Atlantic. FAO Species Catalogue for Fishery Purposes no. 7, Food and Agriculture Organization, Rome." type="journal volume" year="2013">Ebert &amp; Stehmann 2013</bibRefCitation>
). Studies are currently ongoing to determine the relationship between these two species.
</subSubSection>
</paragraph>
